1
00:00:01,177 --> 00:00:20,996
So I thought this month we'd have a look at this fear and anxiety since there's so much of it.

2
00:00:22,097 --> 00:00:27,522
No need to mention names, what's causing all the problems.

3
00:00:28,734 --> 00:00:39,104
I mean, there are words in Pali which separate fear and anxiety, but for our purposes, we can put them all into just this word fear.

4
00:00:42,106 --> 00:00:50,634
The way we experience fear is a sudden jolt of bad energy in the body and it tends to go away.

5
00:00:50,734 --> 00:00:56,020
So if you step out on the road and a car just misses you, you get that fright.

6
00:00:57,100 --> 00:00:58,201
Whereas

7
00:00:58,603 --> 00:01:03,290
And it tends to be paralyzing and cold, I think.

8
00:01:03,991 --> 00:01:06,174
Whereas anxiety is something long-term.

9
00:01:06,234 --> 00:01:07,796
It's always about the future.

10
00:01:07,856 --> 00:01:09,579
It's always what's going to happen next.

11
00:01:10,480 --> 00:01:13,965
And we tend to feel that as an agitation.

12
00:01:13,986 --> 00:01:16,349
And it warms us up.

13
00:01:16,430 --> 00:01:17,251
It heats us up.

14
00:01:17,650 --> 00:01:20,835
So there's quite a sort of a difference between them.

15
00:01:21,716 --> 00:01:25,843
But for our purposes, as I say, you know, fear will do.

16
00:01:26,447 --> 00:01:31,713
So whenever we talk about things like this, always go back to the root problem.

17
00:01:32,334 --> 00:01:35,018
And there, of course, we find the dear old self.

18
00:01:35,838 --> 00:01:41,965
So this is the delusion of some body, some person which has a reality to it.

19
00:01:42,846 --> 00:01:47,191
So remember that even the Buddha has a personality.

20
00:01:47,212 --> 00:01:51,257
It's not as though you lose your personality when you become liberated.

21
00:01:51,641 --> 00:02:14,139
uh but you lose that sort of uh sense of self being isolated from uh a sense of disconnect and this manifests of course mainly uh when we come across death so that's our old our old friend death and um anything that anything that suggests

22
00:02:14,322 --> 00:02:21,731
endings always reminds us of that ultimate state, which, you know, brings fear.

23
00:02:24,094 --> 00:02:26,518
It's the unknowability when it'll happen.

24
00:02:26,598 --> 00:02:28,439
We don't know what will happen after death.

25
00:02:28,500 --> 00:02:31,985
We might have a certain faith, a certain belief that we carry on.

26
00:02:32,925 --> 00:02:34,929
On the other hand, we might think we just disappear.

27
00:02:35,889 --> 00:02:39,655
But whatever it is, nobody actually wants to die.

28
00:02:41,389 --> 00:02:53,966
Now, from that sense of self, of course, we try to buffer ourselves against the world to protect ourselves from the world and from that fear of losing.

29
00:02:54,266 --> 00:02:58,872
So we attach to things, you know, we gather wealth, friends, power.

30
00:02:59,794 --> 00:03:07,043
We like to absorb into sensual pleasures and become attached to that sort of thing, going on holidays, sex, drugs, rock and roll.

31
00:03:09,266 --> 00:03:17,194
And of course, the more things we have, the more people, the friends and etc., etc., the more we can lose.

32
00:03:17,694 --> 00:03:21,498
And therefore, with that attachment, there also comes fear.

33
00:03:23,099 --> 00:03:25,983
So the Buddha in the Dhammapada states it quite clearly.

34
00:03:26,143 --> 00:03:27,884
From attachment comes grief.

35
00:03:28,485 --> 00:03:30,227
From attachment comes fear.

36
00:03:31,308 --> 00:03:33,651
One who is free from attachment has no grief.

37
00:03:34,451 --> 00:03:35,932
So how can there be fear?

38
00:03:39,354 --> 00:03:41,137
So how do we overcome it?

39
00:03:41,298 --> 00:03:44,141
Well, first of all, there's just the reflection.

40
00:03:44,322 --> 00:03:54,575
So we've done, you know, in a past moon celebration, we wandered into the idea of death, sickness, aging and all that.

41
00:03:55,197 --> 00:04:04,889
And it's sort of bringing that up as often as we want just to get accustomed to the idea of sickness, aging and death.

42
00:04:06,439 --> 00:04:20,115
And it's through it's through that sort of a cusp that that sense of being OK with the feelings that come up with that, that is part of purifying the heart of its fear of it.

43
00:04:21,137 --> 00:04:21,437
Yeah.

44
00:04:22,538 --> 00:04:28,026
So one who is wise and full of insight does not tremble in the face of death.

45
00:04:30,588 --> 00:04:31,889
And then there's meta.

46
00:04:32,110 --> 00:04:33,151
Now you have to be careful.

47
00:04:33,252 --> 00:04:38,502
Meta isn't there to sort of bury it, to push it away, to sort of suppress it.

48
00:04:38,882 --> 00:04:41,607
Meta is there as a way of approaching it.

49
00:04:42,208 --> 00:04:42,548
Yeah.

50
00:04:42,869 --> 00:04:47,617
I'm sure you've heard me speak about holding things with that sense of care.

51
00:04:48,319 --> 00:04:48,899
So if

52
00:04:49,235 --> 00:04:57,702
We find ourselves being anxious, being afraid of things, especially with the news and all that.

53
00:04:58,185 --> 00:05:02,197
And it can bring up a certain sense of fear and anxiety about what's happening in the world.

54
00:05:02,464 --> 00:05:07,492
Just to stay with the feeling and to embrace it with a sense of care.

55
00:05:07,793 --> 00:05:13,322
And remember, you can always talk to the heart, you know, dear heart, I can feel you.

56
00:05:13,362 --> 00:05:20,855
I know you're in a dreadful state, but, you know, we'll just stay here for a little while and I'm sure that you'll release that energy.

57
00:05:21,156 --> 00:05:21,536
See?

58
00:05:22,040 --> 00:05:34,119
So by creating that sort of distance between what you're feeling and what is doing the feeling, you're allowing that energy to dissipate.

59
00:05:34,860 --> 00:05:41,110
So that's a way of coming to terms with fear and of allowing that sensation to die away.

60
00:05:44,295 --> 00:05:47,860
So what we're heading for, of course, is fearlessness.

61
00:05:48,701 --> 00:05:49,684
And

62
00:05:50,153 --> 00:05:53,476
Part of the practice of Vipassana is to do with that.

63
00:05:53,576 --> 00:05:55,779
But remember, you can do it at any time.

64
00:05:56,261 --> 00:06:10,059
Any time you, you know, if you're, if there's the occasion, if you're on your own, for instance, as you'll see from a reading that I'll be giving from the discourses, you can just sit with it for a while.

65
00:06:10,199 --> 00:06:10,699
That's all.

66
00:06:11,259 --> 00:06:14,324
And you just, you know, sometimes it can be quite, quite heavy.

67
00:06:14,423 --> 00:06:16,687
I mean, even feelings of nausea.

68
00:06:17,228 --> 00:06:19,029
So you just sit with it, you see.

69
00:06:19,735 --> 00:06:25,444
And that that lack of reaction because, you know, allows the heart to heal itself.

70
00:06:25,685 --> 00:06:35,000
So remember, every time we're reacting, pushing it away, the energy of pushing it away is actually becoming part of that of that fear.

71
00:06:36,002 --> 00:06:42,334
And if we make if we allow the anxiety to run away with those thoughts, then it's going to grow.

72
00:06:42,651 --> 00:06:55,848
So with those two opposite, those two ways of dealing with it, you know, as soon as we realize we're doing that, stop, you know, and just open up to what the heart wants to say.

73
00:07:00,375 --> 00:07:07,163
So, OK, so I've just chosen a passage really to to show us how the Buddha himself dealt with it.

74
00:07:07,584 --> 00:07:09,646
And it's much the same as we've been talking.

75
00:07:09,687 --> 00:07:12,591
So it's nice to know that he went through the same problems.

76
00:07:13,735 --> 00:07:18,141
So it's called the discourse of fear and dread.

77
00:07:19,483 --> 00:07:22,228
And a Brahmin, Janusoni, goes to see him.

78
00:07:22,689 --> 00:07:26,173
And there's the usual exchange of greetings and little niceties.

79
00:07:26,694 --> 00:07:33,947
And then he says to the Buddha, remote jungle thicket places in the forest are hard to endure.

80
00:07:34,788 --> 00:07:39,995
Seclusion is hard to practice and it is hard to enjoy solitude.

81
00:07:40,516 --> 00:07:47,206
One would think the jungles would rob a meditator of their minds if they have no concentration.

82
00:07:48,187 --> 00:07:49,709
So the Buddha agrees with that.

83
00:07:49,949 --> 00:07:58,584
And then he lists a whole load of things that if we suffer from these things, it's going to be hard to sit in solitude.

84
00:07:59,444 --> 00:08:03,992
So it's unpurified of bodily conduct, verbal conduct.

85
00:08:04,293 --> 00:08:26,841
Covetousness and full of lust, ill will and intentions of hate, sloth and torpor, restlessness and unpeacefulness in mind, uncertain and doubtful, given to self-praise and disparaging others, subject to alarm and terror, that suggests trauma to me.

86
00:08:27,377 --> 00:08:41,474
desirous of gain, honour and renown, lazy and wanting in energy, unmindful and not fully aware, unconcentrated, with straying minds, devoid of wisdom, idiots.

87
00:08:42,254 --> 00:08:51,945
Such people will find it very difficult to find solitude in the forests, in the jungle thicket resting places.

88
00:08:53,265 --> 00:08:56,490
So now he says of himself that...

89
00:08:56,875 --> 00:09:00,423
He felt that he wasn't suffering from all that very much.

90
00:09:01,405 --> 00:09:10,287
And so he decides there are especially auspicious nights of the 14th, 15th and the 8th of the fortnight.

91
00:09:10,648 --> 00:09:12,572
So this is the moon calendar.

92
00:09:13,294 --> 00:09:25,267
Now, what if on such nights as these I were to dwell in such awe-inspiring, hair-raising abodes as orchard shrines, woodland shrines and tree shrines?

93
00:09:25,868 --> 00:09:30,993
So these shrines were where the gods were and some of them weren't particularly nice.

94
00:09:33,014 --> 00:09:42,524
Interestingly enough, he doesn't he doesn't here suggest that he went to sit in the charnel grounds

95
00:09:43,078 --> 00:09:44,807
to overcome the fear of death.

96
00:09:44,847 --> 00:09:49,730
Here he is talking about these shrines and of course he's there during the night.

97
00:09:51,347 --> 00:09:58,778
I dwelt in such awe-inspiring, horrifying abodes as orchard shrines, woodland shrines and tree shrines.

98
00:09:58,999 --> 00:10:07,532
And while I dwelt there, a wild animal would come up to me or a peacock would knock off a branch or a wind would rustle the leaves.

99
00:10:07,552 --> 00:10:12,119
And I thought, what now if this is the fear and dread coming, right?

100
00:10:12,139 --> 00:10:15,583
So he's gone to experience this fear and dread.

101
00:10:16,725 --> 00:10:21,152
And then I thought, why do I always dwell expecting fear and dread?

102
00:10:21,553 --> 00:10:28,241
What if I soothe that fear and dread while keeping the same posture that I'm in when it comes upon me?

103
00:10:28,922 --> 00:10:31,225
So he stops expecting this fear and dread.

104
00:10:31,325 --> 00:10:32,966
However, it does come.

105
00:10:33,648 --> 00:10:37,692
And he says, while I walked, the fear and dread came upon me.

106
00:10:38,052 --> 00:10:44,220
I neither stood nor sat nor lay down till I had soothed that fear and dread.

107
00:10:44,825 --> 00:10:47,928
While I stood, the fear and dread came upon me.

108
00:10:48,249 --> 00:10:53,836
I neither walked nor sat nor lay down till I had soothed the fear and dread.

109
00:10:54,557 --> 00:10:57,921
And while I sat, the fear and dread came upon me.

110
00:10:58,461 --> 00:11:03,688
I neither walked nor stood nor lay down till I had soothed the fear and dread.

111
00:11:04,490 --> 00:11:07,974
And while I lay down, the fear and dread came upon me.

112
00:11:08,495 --> 00:11:14,341
I neither walked nor stood nor sat down till I had soothed that fear of dread.

113
00:11:15,182 --> 00:11:20,309
So there he is, you see, he went through the same sort of rubbish that we have to go through.

114
00:11:21,812 --> 00:11:26,979
Now, so that's to do with, shall we say, fear as something unwholesome.

115
00:11:27,298 --> 00:11:29,822
But interestingly enough, fear can be wholesome.

116
00:11:30,663 --> 00:11:33,967
And one writer calls it the paradox of fear.

117
00:11:35,517 --> 00:11:37,499
So take a very simple instance.

118
00:11:38,461 --> 00:11:41,403
Why don't we just step out on the road and cross to the other side?

119
00:11:41,865 --> 00:11:41,985
Right.

120
00:11:42,004 --> 00:11:45,548
Because, you know, within us, there's a fear of being knocked over.

121
00:11:46,509 --> 00:11:53,457
And it's reminding ourselves of that, even if it's only in the background, even if it's only, say, subconscious.

122
00:11:53,538 --> 00:12:00,647
We know that if we don't take care and we walk out into the road, you know, we may very well have a serious accident.

123
00:12:01,318 --> 00:12:08,450
So there are two qualities that he points to, which are, shall we say, wholesome fear.

124
00:12:09,130 --> 00:12:12,755
And that's the dread of consequences and shame.

125
00:12:14,217 --> 00:12:20,267
So he gives a whole list of things that we should be afraid of in terms of consequences.

126
00:12:20,386 --> 00:12:22,770
Some of them, you know, pretty straightforward.

127
00:12:23,371 --> 00:12:27,057
Things like misconduct of body, speech and mind.

128
00:12:27,475 --> 00:12:32,418
But he also talks about famine, catastrophes, schisms.

129
00:12:34,081 --> 00:12:45,669
So these things are, should we say, being afraid, being afraid of famine and catastrophes and things like that.

130
00:12:46,130 --> 00:12:49,693
We prepare for them.

131
00:12:49,714 --> 00:12:49,974
Right.

132
00:12:50,033 --> 00:12:57,279
So, as you know, we've had floods in this country and we finally did have done a little bit about them.

133
00:12:57,648 --> 00:13:10,644
So knowing that there are going to be catastrophes, there are going to be famines, you build up a situations where you can undermine them.

134
00:13:11,384 --> 00:13:38,116
so this fear of things going wrong and the fear of doing things which are unwholesome and will have consequences that sort of fear is a wholesome fear it stops us doing things or it makes us do things for our own personal benefit the other one is shame so shame is you know when we feel that we've lost

135
00:13:38,350 --> 00:13:43,339
a steam in people's eyes if we do something that they see or hear.

136
00:13:44,620 --> 00:13:47,346
And that, of course, is something that we don't like at all.

137
00:13:48,047 --> 00:14:01,692
But it's also at times when we have thought something or we do something where nobody's around, but we just feel that, you know, it's not something that I expect of myself.

138
00:14:02,278 --> 00:14:07,583
I had an old aunt who used to say, if I did that, it wouldn't be me.

139
00:14:07,985 --> 00:14:24,941
So it's that sort of understanding about how we feel when we do something that humiliates us, that we feel that our worthiness in people's eyes and in our own eyes has been undermined.

140
00:14:25,601 --> 00:14:29,586
So fear and dread of consequences...

141
00:14:29,886 --> 00:14:33,650
in the Buddha's understanding, are actually our guardians.

142
00:14:34,331 --> 00:14:36,514
They stop us doing unwholesome things.

143
00:14:37,695 --> 00:14:43,760
And it's interesting that the academics who study this are sort of confounded by it.

144
00:14:43,780 --> 00:14:47,965
I mean, to me, it seems pretty straightforward, you know.

145
00:14:48,745 --> 00:14:53,932
So one of them conjured up this phrase, the paradox of fear.

146
00:14:56,114 --> 00:14:57,294
Okay, so...

147
00:14:57,815 --> 00:15:26,581
There we have it, you know, in short, how the roots of fear and anxiety based on this self and attachment to things, how we deal with it through loving kindness and insights, vipassana, and allowing that energy to dissipate and how some fears that we have and some loss of face, the fear of the loss of face are actually our protectors.

148
00:15:26,981 --> 00:15:27,282
Yeah.

149
00:15:29,927 --> 00:15:30,549
Very good.

150
00:15:30,789 --> 00:15:43,802
So I can only hope my words have been of some assistance and that by your careful investigation of fear, you will be liberated from all fear sooner rather than later.

